  <body>
    <button id="theme-toggle" title="Toggle dark mode">🌙 Dark Mode</button>    <p><strong>productivePlace of Examination:</strong></p>
    <ol>
      <li>OPD</li>
      <li>Ward</li>
      <li>ER</li>
    </ol>
    <h3 class="section-title">I. IDENTIFICATION DATA</h3>
    <p><strong>Name of Patient:</strong> [Full Name]</p>
    <p><strong>Age:</strong> [Years, Months, Days] </p>
    <details>
      <ol>
        <li> <strong>&lt;&nbsp; 24 h = Pathological):</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Hemolytic Disease of the Newborn:
              <ul>
                <li>Rh Incompatibility</li>
                <li>ABO Incompatibility</li>
                <li>Minor blood group incompatibilities</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>Red blood cell enzyme defects (e.g., </li>
            <ul>
              <li>G6PD deficiency, </li>
              <li>pyruvate kinase deficiency)</li>
            </ul>
            <li>Red blood cell membrane defects (e.g., </li>
            <ul>
              <li>hereditary spherocytosis, </li>
              <li>elliptocytosis)</li>
            </ul>
            <li>Congenital Infections (TORCH - </li>
            <ul>
              <li>Toxoplasmosis, </li>
              <li>Other (syphilis, varicella-zoster, parvovirus B19), </li>
              <li>Rubella, </li>
              <li>Cytomegalovirus, </li>
              <li>Herpes simplex)</li>
            </ul>
            <li>Sepsis</li>
            <li>Crigler-Najjar Syndrome (Type I - severe)</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li> <strong>&gt;&nbsp; 24 hours ~ Physio, can also be path:</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Physiological Jaundice (most common, usually mild and resolves
              spontaneously)</li>
            <li>Breastfeeding Jaundice (suboptimal milk intake, dehydration,
              usually in the first week)</li>
            <li>Breast Milk Jaundice (appears later, around day 4-7, can persist
              for weeks/months; infant is otherwise well)</li>
            <li>Sepsis/Infection (UTI, systemic infections)</li>
            <li>Polycythemia</li>
            <li>Increased enterohepatic circulation (e.g., from bowel
              obstruction, meconium ileus)</li>
            <li>Hypothyroidism (usually presents later but can be a cause of
              prolonged jaundice)</li>
            <li>Crigler-Najjar Syndrome (Type II - milder form)</li>
            <li>Gilbert's Syndrome (may become apparent, though often diagnosed
              later)</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li> <strong>Prolonged Neonatal Jaundice (persisting &gt;2 weeks in
            term, &gt;3 weeks in preterm infants):</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Breast Milk Jaundice</li>
            <li>Biliary Atresia (conjugated hyperbilirubinemia, acholic stools -
              surgical emergency)</li>
            <li>Neonatal Hepatitis (idiopathic or infectious)</li>
            <li>Hypothyroidism</li>
            <li>Galactosemia</li>
            <li>Alpha-1 Antitrypsin Deficiency</li>
            <li>Choledochal cyst</li>
            <li>Inspissated bile syndrome</li>
            <li>Urinary Tract Infection</li>
            <li>Congenital infections (TORCH)</li>
            <li>Gilbert's syndrome, Crigler-Najjar syndrome</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li> <strong>INFANCY (1 month to 1 year)</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>prolonged neonatal jaundice (e.g., Biliary Atresia, Alpha-1
              Antitrypsin Deficiency, choledochal cyst).</li>
            <li>Viral Hepatitis (less common than in older children, but
              Hepatitis A, B, C can occur)</li>
            <li>Metabolic Liver Diseases (e.g., Tyrosinemia, cystic fibrosis,
              Wilson's disease (rarely this early),)</li>
            <li>Drug-induced liver injury</li>
            <li>Severe infections/Sepsis</li>
            <li>Hemolytic Anemias (if not diagnosed in neonatal period)</li>
            <li>Alagille Syndrome</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li> <strong>OLDER CHILDREN (1 year to Adolescence)</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Viral Hepatitis (Hepatitis A is most common in this group;
              Hepatitis B, C, E, EBV, CMV))</li>
            <li>Drug-Induced Liver Injury (e.g., paracetamol overdose, certain
              antibiotics, antiepileptics)</li>
            <li>Gilbert's Syndrome (often unmasked by intercurrent illness,
              fasting, or stress)</li>
            <li>Autoimmune Hepatitis</li>
            <li>Wilson's Disease (typically presents from age 5 upwards)</li>
            <li>Alpha-1 Antitrypsin Deficiency</li>
            <li>Cholelithiasis (gallstones) and Choledocholithiasis (stones in
              bile duct) - less common than adults but increasing, risk factors
              include obesity, hemolytic anemias, TPN.</li>
            <li>Choledochal Cyst</li>
            <li>Hemolytic Anemias (e.g., sickle cell disease crisis, hereditary
              spherocytosis)</li>
            <li>Chronic Liver Disease leading to cirrhosis (rarer)</li>
            <li>Tumors affecting liver or biliary tree (rare)</li>
            <li>Leptospirosis</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li> <strong>ADULTS</strong>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Pre-hepatic (mainly unconjugated hyperbilirubinemia):</strong>
              <ul>
                <li>Hemolysis (e.g., autoimmune hemolytic anemia, hereditary
                  spherocytosis, G6PD deficiency, sickle cell anemia)</li>
                <li>Ineffective erythropoiesis (e.g., pernicious anemia,
                  thalassemia)</li>
                <li>Gilbert's Syndrome</li>
                <li>Crigler-Najjar Syndrome (Type II)</li>
                <li>Drugs (e.g., rifampicin, probenecid)</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Hepatic ( hepatocellular - can be mixed
                conjugated/unconjugated):</strong>
              <ul>
                <li>Viral Hepatitis (Acute or Chronic - Hepatitis A, B, C, D, E;
                  EBV, CMV)</li>
                <li>Alcoholic Liver Disease (fatty liver, alcoholic hepatitis,
                  cirrhosis)</li>
                <li>Non-Alcoholic Fatty Liver Disease (NAFLD) / Non-Alcoholic
                  Steatohepatitis (NASH)</li>
                <li>Drug-Induced Liver Injury (DILI - numerous drugs)</li>
                <li>Autoimmune Hepatitis</li>
                <li>Cirrhosis (from any chronic liver disease - leads to
                  impaired bilirubin processing and excretion)</li>
                <li>Primary Biliary Cholangitis (PBC)</li>
                <li>Primary Sclerosing Cholangitis (PSC)</li>
                <li>Wilson's Disease</li>
                <li>Hereditary Hemochromatosis</li>
                <li>Alpha-1 Antitrypsin Deficiency</li>
                <li>Liver Metastases or Primary Hepatocellular Carcinoma</li>
                <li>Sepsis / Systemic infections causing hepatic dysfunction</li>
                <li>Leptospirosis</li>
                <li>Budd-Chiari Syndrome</li>
                <li>Veno-occlusive disease</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Post-hepatic (obstructive - mainly conjugated
                hyperbilirubinemia):</strong>
              <ul>
                <li>Choledocholithiasis (gallstones in the common bile duct -
                  most common cause)</li>
                <li>Pancreatic Cancer (especially head of pancreas)</li>
                <li>Cholangiocarcinoma (bile duct cancer)</li>
                <li>Ampullary Cancer</li>
                <li>Strictures of the bile duct (post-surgical, PSC, chronic
                  pancreatitis)</li>
                <li>Chronic Pancreatitis causing biliary compression</li>
                <li>Parasitic infections of the biliary tree (e.g., Ascaris,
                  Clonorchis)</li>
                <li>Mirizzi Syndrome</li>
                <li>External compression of the bile duct (e.g., lymph nodes,
                  tumors)</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </details>
    <p><strong>Sex:</strong></p>
    <ol>
      <li>Male</li>
      <li>Female</li>
      <li>Other</li>
    </ol>
