    <p></p>
    <p><strong>Family Type:</strong></p>
    <ol>
      <li>Nuclear</li>
      <li>Joint</li>
      <li>Extended</li>
    </ol>
    <p><strong>Father's Name:</strong> </p>
    <strong> </strong>
    <p></p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Age:</strong><strong></strong></li>
      <li><strong>Occupation:</strong> </li>
      <li>&nbsp;<strong>Education:</strong></li>
    </ol>
    <p><strong>Mother's Name:</strong> </p>
    <p></p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Age:</strong><strong></strong></li>
      <li><strong>Occupation:</strong> </li>
      <li>&nbsp;<strong>Education:</strong> </li>
    </ol>
    <p><strong>Socioeconomic Status:</strong></p>
    <ol>
      <li>Kuppuswamy Scale
        <ol>
          <li>Score</li>
          <li>Class</li>
        </ol>
      </li>
      <li>BPL</li>
      <li>APL</li>
    </ol>
    <p><br>
      <strong>Date:</strong> [Date of Consultation]&nbsp; <strong>Time:</strong>
      [Time of Consultation]</p>
    <p><strong>Informant:</strong> </p>
    <ol>
      <li>Name and Relationship to Patient</li>
    </ol>
    <p></p>
    <p class="detail-prompt"><em>Reliability of Informant:</em></p>
    <ol>
      <li>Good</li>
      <li>Fair</li>
      <li>Poor</li>
    </ol>
    <h3 class="section-title">II. CHIEF COMPLAINTS</h3>
    <p class="detail-prompt">(In chronological order of appearance, with
      duration; maximum 3-4 complaints ideally)</p>
    <ol>
      <li>Fall<br>
      </li>
      <li>pain<br>
      </li>
      <li>Diarrhoea<br>
      </li>
      <li>vomiting</li>
    </ol>
    <h3 class="section-title">III. HISTORY OF PRESENT ILLNESS (HPI)</h3>
    <p class="detail-prompt">(Elaborate on each chief complaint: onset,
      duration, progress, severity, aggravating/relieving factors, associated
      symptoms, treatment taken, and response. For systemic illnesses, describe
      the evolution of symptoms.)</p>
    <p>[Detailed narrative of the illness]</p>
    <h2>Elaboration of Presenting Complaint: Vomiting (based on video content)</h2>
    <h2><a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VezCFksfWg4" target="_blank">Nausea
        and Vomiting Part 5 - Differential diagnosis</a></h2>
    <div class="video-container"> <iframe src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/VezCFksfWg4"

        title="Nausea and Vomiting Part 5 - Differential diagnosis" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; clipboard-write; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture; web-share"

        referrerpolicy="strict-origin-when-cross-origin" allowfullscreen=""></iframe>
    </div>
    <br>
    <ul>
      <li> <strong>S: Site</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Vomiting is a systemic/gastrointestinal symptom; "site" is not
            directly applicable to the act of vomiting.</li>
          <li>Site of any associated pain is crucial:
            <ul>
              <li>Helps differentiate intra-peritoneal vs. extra-peritoneal
                causes (general concept from video).</li>
              <li class="pediatric">In children, diffuse abdominal pain is
                common.</li>
              <li class="pediatric">Localized pain might suggest specific
                pediatric pathologies (e.g., appendicitis in Right Lower
                Quadrant, intussusception).</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><em>Site of vomiting itself cannot be directly assigned from this
              video's content, but relevant for associated symptoms.</em></li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>O: Onset</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Varies based on the underlying cause:
            <ul>
              <li>Acute:
                <ul>
                  <li>Video suggests food poisoning, viral gastroenteritis.</li>
                  <li class="pediatric">Very common in children due to
                    infections (viral gastroenteritis is a leading cause).</li>
                  <li class="pediatric">Can also be due to food intolerances or
                    acute surgical conditions (e.g., appendicitis,
                    intussusception).</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li>Chronic or Recurrent:
                <ul>
                  <li>Video suggests pregnancy, Meniere's disease,
                    gastroparesis.</li>
                  <div class="pediatric">
                    <li>GERD</li>
                    <li>Eosinophilic esophagitis</li>
                    <li>Cyclic vomiting syndrome</li>
                    <li>Metabolic disorders</li>
                    <li>Increased intracranial pressure (e.g., from a tumor)</li>
                    <li>Pyloric stenosis (presents with progressively worsening
                      vomiting in infants).</li>
                  </div>
                </ul>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>Clinician inquiry: Sudden or gradual onset?</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>D: Duration</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Acute (short duration):
            <ul>
              <li>Video: Food poisoning.</li>
              <li class="pediatric">Most viral gastroenteritis episodes in
                children are self-limiting (few days to a week).</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>Long-term/Recurrent:
            <ul>
              <li>Video: </li>
              <li>Gastroparesis, </li>
              <li>pregnancy.</li>
              <div class="pediatric">
                <li>GERD</li>
                <li>Cyclic vomiting syndrome</li>
                <li>Food allergies/intolerances</li>
                <li>Metabolic conditions</li>
                <li>Anatomical abnormalities (e.g., malrotation with
                  intermittent volvulus).</li>
              </div>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>A: Aggravating / Relieving Factors</strong>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Exacerbating Factors (Aggravating):</strong> </li>
          <li>Specific foods/recent meal:</li>
          <ul>
            <li>Video: Can point to food poisoning. [Video Ref: 22:40]</li>
            <div class="pediatric">
              <li>Specific formula or food introduction can trigger vomiting
                (e.g., Cow's Milk Protein Allergy - CMPA, food intolerance).</li>
              <li>Overfeeding can be a factor in infants.</li>
            </div>
            <li>Medications:</li>
            <ul>
              <li>Video: Chemotherapy drugs, apomorphine, digoxin derivatives,
                opioids, NSAIDs. [Video Ref: 23:05]</li>
              <li class="pediatric">Antibiotics are a common cause in children.</li>
            </ul>
            <li>Eating:</li>
            <ul>
              <li>Video implies exacerbation in gastric outlet obstruction
                (post-prandial timing).</li>
              <div class="pediatric">
                <li>Pyloric stenosis: Vomiting typically occurs shortly after
                  feeding.</li>
                <li>GERD: Vomiting/regurgitation can occur during or after
                  feeds, or with changes in position.</li>
              </div>
            </ul>
            <li class="pediatric">Change in position (e.g., lying down after
              feeds in GERD).</li>
            <li class="pediatric">Stress or excitement (can be a trigger in
              cyclic vomiting syndrome).</li>
            <li class="pediatric">Coughing spells (can induce vomiting, e.g., in
              pertussis or other respiratory infections).</li>
          </ul>
          <li><strong>Relieving Factors:</strong> </li>
          <li>Vomiting itself relieves pain:</li>
          <ul>
            <li>Video: Characteristic of Peptic Ulcer Disease (PUD). [Video Ref:
              18:13]</li>
            <div class="pediatric">
              <li>Less common in young children for PUD, but possible.</li>
              <li>Cyclic vomiting syndrome: Episode eventually resolves, often
                with sleep.</li>
            </div>
          </ul>
          <div class="pediatric">
            <li>Burping an infant well after feeds.</li>
            <li>Keeping an infant upright after feeds (for GERD).</li>
            <li>Specific dietary modifications if an allergy/intolerance is
              identified.</li>
          </div>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>C: Character (of vomitus)</strong>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Undigested food particles:</strong> </li>
          <ul>
            <li>Video: Suggests esophageal disorders (e.g., obstruction before
              the stomach). [Video Ref: 13:26]</li>
          </ul>
          <li><strong>Food particles WITHOUT bile (Non-bilious):</strong> </li>
          <ul>
            <li>Video: Suggests gastric outlet obstruction (obstruction before
              bile enters the duodenum). [Video Ref: 14:00]</li>
            <li class="pediatric">Classic for pyloric stenosis in infants.</li>
          </ul>
          <li><strong>Food particles WITH bile (Bilious - often green or dark
              yellow):</strong> </li>
          <ul>
            <li>Video: Suggests small bowel obstruction (obstruction after bile
              enters the duodenum). [Video Ref: 14:40]</li>
            <li class="pediatric"><strong>Bilious vomiting in a neonate is a
                surgical emergency until proven otherwise</strong> (may indicate
              malrotation with volvulus, duodenal atresia, jejunal atresia).</li>
            <li class="pediatric">In older children, can indicate
              intussusception or other obstructions.</li>
          </ul>
          <li><strong>Feculent material (bad odor, like stool):</strong> </li>
          <ul>
            <li>Video: Suggests large bowel obstruction (feculent emesis).
              [Video Ref: 15:30]</li>
            <div class="pediatric">
              <li>Hirschsprung's </li>
              <li>distal intestinal obstruction, or </li>
              <li>severe constipation with overflow.</li>
            </div>
          </ul>
          <li><strong>Projectile emesis:</strong> </li>
          <ul>
            <li>high ICT (CNS cause). [Video Ref: 16:10]</li>
            <div class="pediatric">
              <li>pyloric stenosis in infants (though typically non-bilious).</li>
              <li>severe GERD or forceful vomiting from any cause.</li>
            </div>
          </ul>
          <li class="pediatric"><strong>Bloody (Hematemesis):</strong> </li>
          <ul>
            <li>Bright red: Active bleeding </li>
            <ul>
              <li>Mallory-Weiss tear, </li>
              <li>esophagitis, </li>
              <li>gastritis, </li>
              <li>swallowed maternal blood in neonates).</li>
            </ul>
            <li>Coffee-ground: </li>
            <ul>
              <li>&nbsp;stomach acid (e.g., gastritis, PUD).</li>
            </ul>
          </ul>
          <div class="pediatric">
            <li><strong>Mucus-streaked:</strong> </li>
            <ul>
              <li>respiratory infections and </li>
              <li>post-nasal drip, or with </li>
              <li>gastritis.</li>
            </ul>
            <li><strong>Watery/Clear:</strong> </li>
            <ul>
              <li>early viral gastroenteritis or with </li>
              <li>CNS causes.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <li><em>Other characteristics a clinician might ask about, not
              detailed in this video: amount, consistency.</em></li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>R: Radiation</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Vomiting itself does not "radiate." This is relevant for
            associated pain.</li>
          <li><em>Cannot be directly assigned for "vomiting" itself from video
              content.</em></li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>A: Associated Symptoms</strong>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Abdominal pain:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Video: Can suggest GIT obstruction. [Video Ref: 17:36]</li>
              <li class="pediatric">Colicky, intermittent pain is typical of
                intussusception.</li>
              <li class="pediatric">Constant, worsening pain with appendicitis.</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Pain relieved by vomiting:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Video: Suggests Peptic Ulcer Disease (PUD). [Video Ref: 18:13]</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Fever and/or Diarrhea:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Video: Suggests viral gastroenteritis or general
                gastroenteritis. [Video Ref: 19:05]</li>
              <li class="pediatric">Very common pairing in children.</li>
              <li class="pediatric">High fever itself can sometimes cause
                vomiting in young children.</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Visual disturbances, Headache, Vertigo, Tinnitus:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Video: Suggests Meniere's disease or other CNS issues. [Video
                Ref: 19:26]</li>
              <li class="pediatric">Headache and vomiting (especially morning
                vomiting) can be red flags for increased intracranial pressure
                (e.g., brain tumor, hydrocephalus).</li>
              <li class="pediatric">Lethargy is a significant associated symptom
                with CNS issues.</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Early satiety</strong> (feeling full quickly):
            <ul>
              <li>Video: Suggests gastroparesis. [Video Ref: 20:11]</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Signs of Dehydration:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Video (from physical exam section): Tachycardia, hypotension,
                poor skin turgor. [Video Ref: 25:30, 26:03]</li>
              <li class="pediatric">Children dehydrate more quickly. Look for:
                <ul>
                  <li>Decreased urine output (number of wet diapers)</li>
                  <li>Dry mucous membranes</li>
                  <li>Sunken fontanelle (in infants)</li>
                  <li>Lethargy</li>
                  <li>Absence of tears.</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <div class="pediatric">
            <li><strong>Weight loss or failure to thrive:</strong> Suggests
              chronic issues like malabsorption, severe GERD, metabolic
              disorder, pyloric stenosis.</li>
            <li><strong>Lethargy/Irritability:</strong> Can indicate serious
              illness, dehydration, or CNS involvement.</li>
            <li><strong>Rash:</strong> Could suggest allergic reaction or
              certain infections.</li>
            <li><strong>Jaundice:</strong> May indicate liver disease or biliary
              obstruction.</li>
            <li><strong>Constipation:</strong> Can lead to vomiting.</li>
            <li><strong>Respiratory symptoms (cough, runny nose):</strong>
              Vomiting may be secondary to a respiratory infection.</li>
            <li><strong>"Red currant jelly" stool:</strong> Classic for
              intussusception.</li>
            <li><strong>Palpable abdominal mass:</strong> Could suggest
              intussusception ("sausage-shaped mass"), pyloric stenosis
              ("olive-like mass"), or tumor.</li>
          </div>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>P: Pattern (Timing / Frequency)</strong>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Timing:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Morning (especially in females):
                <ul>
                  <li>Video: Suggests pregnancy (endocrine cause). [Video Ref:
                    7:10]</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li>Morning (any gender):
                <ul>
                  <li>Video: Can suggest CNS causes, uremia, or alcoholic
                    gastritis. [Video Ref: 7:51]</li>
                  <li class="pediatric">Morning vomiting can be a red flag for
                    increased intracranial pressure in children.</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li>Post-prandial (after meals):
                <ul>
                  <li>Video: Can suggest gastroparesis, gastric outlet
                    obstruction, psychogenic causes, or PUD. [Video Ref: 9:48]</li>
                  <li class="pediatric">Vomiting immediately after or during
                    feeds is common in GERD or pyloric stenosis.</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Frequency:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Video: Helps gauge the severity of the illness. [Video Ref:
                6:30]</li>
              <li class="pediatric">The number of vomiting episodes per day is
                critical in assessing dehydration risk.</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <div class="pediatric">
            <li><strong>Cyclic pattern:</strong> Episodes of intense nausea and
              vomiting lasting hours to days, with symptom-free intervals,
              characteristic of Cyclic Vomiting Syndrome.</li>
            <li><strong>Relation to specific activities:</strong> E.g., car
              sickness (motion sickness).</li>
          </div>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>P: Progression</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Video does not detail the progression of a specific patient's
            vomiting illness over time.</li>
          <li class="pediatric">Important to ask if vomiting is worsening (e.g.,
            increasing frequency/forcefulness like in pyloric stenosis), staying
            the same, or improving.</li>
          <li><em>Cannot be directly assigned for the progression of a single
              vomiting episode/illness from video content beyond general
              implications.</em></li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>E: Effect on life</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Video does not cover this.</li>
          <li class="pediatric">Inquire about missed school/daycare, impact on
            feeding and growth (especially infants), effect on sleep, general
            activity level.</li>
          <li><em>Cannot be directly assigned from video content.</em></li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>S: Severity / Scale</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Gauged by <strong>frequency</strong> of vomiting. [Video Ref:
            6:30]</li>
          <li>Indicated by dehydration signs: tachycardia, hypotension, poor
            skin turgor. [Video Ref: 25:30, 26:03]</li>
          <li class="pediatric">Clinical dehydration scales (e.g., WHO,
            Gorelick) are often used in pediatrics, assessing general
            appearance, eyes, mucous membranes, tears, skin turgor, capillary
            refill, pulse, respiration, and urine output.</li>
          <li><em>The video does not mention a numerical severity scale (e.g.,
              0-10) but focuses on clinical indicators.</em></li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <h2><br>
    </h2>
    <h2>Elaboration of Presenting Complaint: Jaundice (with Pediatric Focus)</h2>
    <ul>
      <li> <strong>S: Site (Distribution of Jaundice)</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Where was the jaundice first noticed? (e.g., eyes, face, chest)</li>
          <li>How has it spread? (Progression is often cephalocaudal - head to
            toe)</li>
          <li class="pediatric">In neonates, assessing the extent of jaundice
            (e.g., to the chest, abdomen, or soles of feet using Kramer's rule)
            can give a rough estimate of bilirubin levels, though biochemical
            testing is definitive.</li>
          <li>Is it primarily skin, sclera (eyes), or also mucous membranes
            (e.g., inside the mouth)?</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>O: Onset</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>When was the jaundice first noticed by the patient or caregiver?
            <ul>
              <li class="pediatric"><strong>Neonatal Jaundice:</strong>
                <ul>
                  <li>Physiological: </li>
                  <li>Typically appears after 24 hours of life,</li>
                  <li>&nbsp;peaks around day 3-5, and </li>
                  <li>resolves within 1-2 weeks.</li>
                  <li><br>
                  </li>
                  <li>Pathological: </li>
                  <li>May appear within the first 24 hours of life,</li>
                  <li>&nbsp;rise rapidly, </li>
                  <li>persist longer, or be </li>
                  <li>associated with other concerning signs.</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li class="pediatric">Older Children/Adults: Acute (e.g., viral
                hepatitis, drug-induced, gallstones) vs. Gradual/Insidious
                (e.g., chronic liver disease, malignancy).</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>Was the onset sudden or gradual?</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>D: Duration</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>How long has the jaundice been present?</li>
          <li>Is it constant, or does it fluctuate?</li>
          <li class="pediatric">Physiological jaundice in neonates is transient.</li>
          <li class="pediatric">Prolonged neonatal jaundice (beyond 2 weeks in
            term infants, 3 weeks in preterm) requires investigation.</li>
          <li class="pediatric">In older children, duration helps differentiate
            acute from chronic conditions.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>A: Aggravating / Relieving Factors</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Are there any factors that make the jaundice appear worse? (e.g.,
            illness, fasting, certain </li>
          <li><em>medications </em>- though this is more for underlying cause
            than jaundice itself)</li>
          <li><em>herbal&nbsp; </em>medications</li>
          <li>Are there any factors that make it seem better? (e.g., exposure to
            <b> sunlight </b>- historically and anecdotally for mild neonatal
            jaundice, but phototherapy is the medical treatment).</li>
          <li class="pediatric"><em>Breastfeeding </em>jaundice: May be
            exacerbated by suboptimal milk intake in the first week.</li>
          <li class="pediatric">Breast milk jaundice: Can persist for several
            weeks but the infant is otherwise well; sometimes temporarily
            interrupting breastfeeding can lower bilirubin (done under medical
            guidance).</li>
          <li><em>Relieving factors for jaundice itself are usually related to
              treatment of the underlying cause rather than patient-initiated
              actions.</em></li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>C: Character (of Jaundice and Associated Stool/Urine)</strong>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Color of Jaundice:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Yellowish (common)</li>
              <li>Greenish tint (may suggest prolonged or severe cholestasis
                with biliverdin accumulation)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Urine Color:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Dark urine (tea-colored or cola-colored): Suggests conjugated
                hyperbilirubinemia (bilirubinuria).</li>
              <li>Normal colored urine: May suggest unconjugated
                hyperbilirubinemia (as unconjugated bilirubin is not
                water-soluble and not excreted in urine).</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Stool Color:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Pale or clay-colored (acholic) stools: Strongly suggests
                biliary obstruction (obstructive jaundice), as bilirubin is not
                reaching the gut.
                <ul>
                  <li class="pediatric">A critical sign in neonates, may
                    indicate biliary atresia.</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li>Normal colored stools.</li>
              <li>Dark stools (melena) if there's associated GI bleeding
                contributing to liver issues.</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>R: Radiation</strong>
        <ul>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>A: Associated Symptoms</strong>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>General:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Fever, chills (suggests infection, e.g., hepatitis,
                cholangitis).</li>
              <li>Malaise, fatigue, anorexia (common with liver disease,
                infections).</li>
              <li>Weight loss (concerning for malignancy, chronic infection, or
                severe chronic liver disease).
                <ul>
                  <li class="pediatric">Poor weight gain or failure to thrive in
                    infants/children with jaundice is a significant concern.</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li>Pruritus (itching): Common with cholestasis due to bile salt
                deposition in the skin.</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Gastrointestinal:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Abdominal pain (RUQ pain might suggest gallstones, hepatitis,
                cholangitis).</li>
              <li>Nausea, vomiting (as seen in the previous example, can be
                associated with many causes of jaundice like hepatitis).</li>
              <li>Abdominal distension (ascites in chronic liver disease).</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li class="pediatric"><strong>Neonatal/Infant Specific:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Poor feeding, lethargy, irritability (can be signs of sepsis,
                severe hyperbilirubinemia/kernicterus, or metabolic disease).</li>
              <li>High-pitched cry, abnormal muscle tone, seizures (concerning
                for kernicterus).</li>
              <li>Vomiting (can be seen with sepsis, metabolic disorders,
                galactosemia).</li>
              <li>Hepatosplenomegaly (enlarged liver/spleen on examination).</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Other systems:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Easy bruising or bleeding (due to impaired synthesis of
                clotting factors by the liver).</li>
              <li>Joint pain (arthralgia), muscle pain (myalgia) (can be seen in
                viral hepatitis).</li>
              <li>Neurological changes (confusion, drowsiness, asterixis &ndash;
                signs of hepatic encephalopathy in severe liver disease).</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>P: Progression</strong> (Often covered by Onset, Duration,
        and Pattern, but can be a distinct inquiry about the course of the
        illness)
        <ul>
          <li>Is the jaundice getting progressively deeper yellow?</li>
          <li>Are associated symptoms worsening or improving?</li>
          <li class="pediatric">Tracking bilirubin levels (if known) provides
            objective measure of progression in neonates.</li>
          <li><em>This element often overlaps with Pattern/Timing.</em></li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>P: Pattern (Timing / Evolution)</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>How has the jaundice changed since it was first noticed?
            (Worsening, improving, stable, fluctuating)</li>
          <li class="pediatric">Physiological neonatal jaundice follows a
            predictable pattern of rise and fall. Pathological jaundice may show
            a rapid rise or prolonged course.</li>
          <li>Any previous episodes of jaundice? or siblings? </li>
          <li>&nbsp;Gilbert's or </li>
          <li>Crigler-Najjar, or </li>
          <li>hemolytic diseases).
            <ul>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>E: Effect on life</strong>
        <ul>
          <li class="pediatric">Impact on feeding, activity levels, growth, and
            development in children.</li>
          <li class="pediatric">Parental anxiety and concern, especially with
            neonatal jaundice.</li>
          <li>For older individuals: ability to work, engage in daily
            activities, appetite, sleep.</li>
          <li><em>This section would be filled with patient/caregiver specific
              information.</em></li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>S: Severity / Scale</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Often gauged by the level of bilirubin in blood tests.</li>
          <li>Clinically, the extent of skin discoloration (cephalocaudal
            progression).</li>
          <li>Severity of associated symptoms (e.g., degree of pruritus,
            presence of hepatic encephalopathy, degree of dehydration if
            vomiting is present).</li>
          <li class="pediatric">In neonates, risk of kernicterus is a key aspect
            of severity based on bilirubin levels and risk factors (e.g.,
            prematurity, sepsis, acidosis, hypoalbuminemia). Nomograms (e.g.,
            Bhutani nomogram) are used to assess risk.</li>
          <li><em>A numerical scale for jaundice itself isn't typically used;
              severity is a clinical and biochemical assessment.</em></li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <h3>Additional Contextual Information to Gather (Beyond SODA CRAPPERS
      directly for jaundice):</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Birth History (Pediatric):</strong> Gestational age, birth
        weight, mode of delivery, any birth trauma (e.g., bruising,
        cephalohematoma which can increase bilirubin), maternal blood group and
        Rh status, history of maternal infections.</li>
      <li><strong>Feeding History (Pediatric):</strong> Breastfed or
        formula-fed? Adequacy of feeding, frequency, volume. Any difficulties
        with feeding.</li>
      <li><strong>Family History:</strong> Liver disease, hemolytic anemias
        (e.g., sickle cell, spherocytosis), Gilbert's syndrome, Crigler-Najjar
        syndrome, gallstones, metabolic disorders.
        <div class="pediatric">History of jaundice or liver disease in siblings.</div>
      </li>
      <li><strong>Medication History:</strong> Any new medications, herbal
        remedies, supplements (potential for drug-induced liver injury).
        <div class="pediatric">Maternal medications during pregnancy or
          breastfeeding.</div>
      </li>
      <li><strong>Travel History:</strong> To areas endemic for hepatitis
        viruses.</li>
      <li><strong>Exposure History:</strong> Blood transfusions, IV drug use,
        high-risk sexual contact (risk factors for viral hepatitis).
        Contaminated food/water.</li>
      <li><strong>Alcohol History (for older patients).</strong></li>
      <li><strong>Vaccination History (Pediatric/Adult):</strong> Hepatitis A
        and B vaccinations.</li>
    </ul>
    <h2><br>
    </h2>
    <h2><br>
    </h2>
    <h2>Elaboration of Presenting Complaint: Cough (SODA CRAPPERS Framework)</h2>
    <ul>
      <li> <strong>S: Site (Perceived Origin)</strong>
        <ul>
          <li><em>Wet vs. Dry (see Character) can also give clues to the
              site/level of airway involvement.</em></li>
          <li>Does the cough feel like it's coming from the throat, chest, or
            elsewhere?</li>
          <ul>
            <li>tickling sensation in the throat (suggesting upper airway)?</li>
          </ul>
          <ul>
            <li>Is it a deep cough felt in the chest (suggesting lower airway)?</li>
          </ul>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>O: Onset</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>sudden </li>
          <li>gradual?</li>
          <li>Categorization by duration (as per your C-MINT related points):
            <ul>
              <li>Acute: &lt; 3 weeks</li>
              <li>Subacute: 3-8 weeks</li>
              <li>Chronic: &gt; 8 weeks </li>
              <li class="pediatric">In children, chronic cough is often defined
                as &gt; 4 weeks.</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>D: Duration</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>How long has this particular episode of coughing been present?</li>
          <li>If recurrent, how long do episodes typically last? How frequent
            are the episodes?</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>A: Aggravating / Relieving Factors (incorporating your
          C-MINT related A/R)</strong>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Aggravating Factors:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Positional changes? (e.g., worse when lying flat - suggestive
                of post-nasal drip, GERD, heart failure)</li>
              <li>Time of day (Diurnal Variations)?
                <ul>
                  <li>Worse at night/early morning? (Asthma, post-nasal drip,
                    GERD)</li>
                  <li class="pediatric">Nocturnal cough is a key indicator for
                    asthma in children.</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li>Seasonal variations? (Allergic rhinitis, asthma triggered by
                seasonal allergens)</li>
              <li>Exposure to irritants (smoke, dust, fumes, strong odors)?</li>
              <li>Cold air?</li>
              <li>Exercise or exertion? (Exercise-induced
                asthma/bronchoconstriction)</li>
              <li>Talking or laughing?</li>
              <li>Eating or drinking? (Aspiration, GERD, tracheo-esophageal
                fistula in infants)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Relieving Factors:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Specific positions? (e.g., sitting up)</li>
              <li>Medications (e.g., inhalers, cough suppressants, antacids)?</li>
              <li>Warm drinks, honey (for symptomatic relief)?</li>
              <li>Steam inhalation?</li>
              <li>Avoiding known triggers?</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>C: Character / Nature / Type (incorporating your C-MINT
          related points 1 &amp; 5)</strong>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Dry</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Dry Cough (Non-productive): </li>
              <li>Often irritating, tickling.</li>
              <li>Common in viral infections, asthma, GERD, ACE inhibitor use,
                interstitial lung disease, early pneumonia.</li>
              <li class="pediatric">Habit cough, psychogenic cough.</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>
            <ul>
            </ul>
            <strong><strong>Productive <br>
              </strong></strong></li>
          <ul>
            <li><strong><strong></strong>Amount:</strong> Scant, moderate,
              copious? </li>
            <li><strong>Color:</strong> Clear, white (mucoid - viral, chronic
              bronchitis), yellow, green (purulent - bacterial infection), rusty
              (pneumococcal pneumonia), pink frothy (pulmonary edema)?
              <div class="pediatric">Green/yellow sputum doesn't always mean
                bacterial infection in children, can be seen with viral too.</div>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Consistency:</strong> Thin, thick, tenacious?</li>
            <li><strong>Odor:</strong> Foul-smelling (anaerobic infection,
              bronchiectasis, lung abscess)?</li>
            <li><strong>Blood (Hemoptysis):</strong> Streaks of blood, frank
              blood? (Needs urgent evaluation - TB, malignancy, bronchiectasis,
              PE, severe infection).</li>
            <li>Common in bronchitis, pneumonia, bronchiectasis, COPD
              exacerbation, cystic fibrosis.</li>
          </ul>
          <li><strong>Sound/Quality of Cough:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Barking (like a seal): Croup (laryngotracheobronchitis).</li>
              <li>Paroxysmal (fits of coughing): Pertussis (whooping cough),
                asthma, aspiration.
                <ul>
                  <li class="pediatric">Associated inspiratory "whoop" in
                    pertussis. Post-tussive emesis common in pertussis.</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li>Hacking: Often seen with smoking or chronic irritation.</li>
              <li>Wheezy cough: Asthma, bronchiolitis.</li>
              <li>Brassy: Tracheal compression.</li>
              <li>Bovine (non-explosive, weak): Vocal cord paralysis,
                neuromuscular weakness.</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>R: Radiation</strong>
        <ul>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>A: Associated Symptoms</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Fever, chills (infection).</li>
          <li>Shortness of breath (dyspnea) - at rest or on exertion (pneumonia,
            asthma, COPD, heart failure, PE).</li>
          <li>Wheezing (asthma, COPD, bronchiolitis).</li>
          <li>Chest pain or tightness (pneumonia, pleurisy, bronchitis, PE,
            cardiac causes, GERD).
            <ul>
              <li>Is the pain pleuritic (worse on inspiration or coughing)?</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>Sore throat, runny nose, nasal congestion (upper respiratory tract
            infection, post-nasal drip).</li>
          <li>Hoarseness or voice changes (laryngitis, GERD, vocal cord issues,
            tumor).</li>
          <li>Heartburn, acid reflux sensation (GERD).</li>
          <li>Fatigue, malaise.</li>
          <li>Body aches (myalgia), joint pain (arthralgia) (viral infections).</li>
          <li>Weight loss, night sweats (TB, malignancy, chronic infection).</li>
          <li>Hemoptysis (coughing up blood - see Character).</li>
        </ul>
        <br>
        <ul class="pediatric">
          <li>Poor feeding or decreased appetite in infants/children.</li>
          <li>Lethargy, irritability in children.</li>
          <li>Cyanosis (bluish discoloration of lips/skin) - serious sign.</li>
          <li>Respiratory distress signs in children: nasal flaring, grunting,
            intercostal/subcostal retractions, tachypnea.</li>
          <li>Apneic spells in infants (can be associated with pertussis or
            severe RSV).</li>
          <li>Stridor (high-pitched inspiratory noise - croup, foreign body,
            laryngomalacia).</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>P: Pattern (Temporal Relationship - overlaps with
          Aggravating/Relieving)</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Continous</li>
          <li>Intermittent</li>
          <ul>
            <li>frequency</li>
          </ul>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>P: Progression</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Is the cough getting better, worse, or staying the same over its
            duration?</li>
          <li>Has the character of the cough changed (e.g., from dry to
            productive)?</li>
          <li>Have new symptoms developed alongside the cough?</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>E: Effect on life</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Impact on sleep (patient's and family members').</li>
          <li>Effect on daily activities, ability to work or attend school.</li>
          <li>Limitation of physical activity or exercise tolerance.</li>
          <li>Social embarrassment or avoidance.</li>
          <li class="pediatric">Impact on feeding, growth, and development in
            children.</li>
          <li class="pediatric">Effect on play and interaction with peers.</li>
          <li>Stress or anxiety related to the cough.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>S: Severity / Scale</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Subjective rating by patient (e.g., on a scale of 0-10, how
            bothersome is it?).</li>
          <li>Frequency of coughing fits (e.g., number of times per hour/day).</li>
          <li>Does it interrupt conversation or activities?</li>
          <li>Does it cause syncope (cough syncope)?</li>
          <li>Does it induce vomiting (post-tussive emesis)?</li>
          <li class="pediatric">Parental assessment of severity, impact on
            child's well-being.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <h3>Additional Contextual Information to Gather for Cough:</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Smoking history (active or passive exposure).
        <div class="pediatric">Exposure to secondhand smoke is a major risk
          factor for respiratory illnesses in children.</div>
      </li>
      <li>Occupational or environmental exposures (dust, chemicals, allergens).</li>
      <li>Past medical history (asthma, COPD, allergies, GERD, heart disease,
        previous pneumonia, TB exposure).
        <div class="pediatric">History of prematurity, congenital lung/heart
          conditions, immunodeficiency, atopy.</div>
      </li>
      <li>Family history (asthma, allergies, cystic fibrosis, alpha-1
        antitrypsin deficiency, TB).</li>
      <li>Medication history (especially ACE inhibitors, beta-blockers).</li>
      <li>Vaccination status (Influenza, Pneumococcus, Pertussis, Measles).</li>
      <li class="pediatric">Possibility of foreign body aspiration (sudden onset
        of choking and coughing, especially in toddlers).</li>
      <li class="pediatric">Daycare attendance (increased exposure to
        infections).</li>
    </ul>
    <h2>Elaboration of Presenting Complaint: Bedwetting (Nocturnal Enuresis)</h2>
    <ul>
      <li> <strong>S: Site</strong>
        <ul>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>O: Onset</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Age when bedwetting started or became a concern.</li>
          <li><strong>Primary Enuresis:</strong> Child has never achieved
            consistent nighttime dryness for at least 6 months.</li>
          <li><em>Secondary </em><strong>Enuresis:</strong> Child achieved at
            least 6 months of nighttime dryness and then started wetting again.
            <ul>
              <li>If secondary, ascertain age of achieving prior dryness and age
                of relapse.</li>
              <li>Any specific triggers or events associated with the onset of
                secondary enuresis (e.g., stress, illness, new sibling, starting
                school)?</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>D: Duration</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>How long has the bedwetting been occurring (for current episode if
            secondary, or overall if primary)?</li>
          <li>If secondary, how long was the period of dryness?</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>A: Aggravating / Relieving Factors</strong>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Aggravating Factors:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Increased fluid intake, especially in the evening/before bed?
                (Type of fluids - e.g., </li>
              <ul>
                <li>caffeinated, </li>
                <li>sugary drinks)</li>
              </ul>
              <li>Stressful events or periods?</li>
              <ul>
                <li>school</li>
                <li>parents fighting</li>
                <li>Social media</li>
                <li>Parental control</li>
                <li><br>
                </li>
              </ul>
              <li>Constipation?</li>
              <li>Deep sleep (child is difficult to arouse)?</li>
              <ul>
                <li>too much play exhausted?</li>
              </ul>
              <li>Cold weather?</li>
              <li>Certain foods or drinks (less common, but some parents report
                associations)?</li>
              <li>Illness (e.g., UTI, viral illness)?</li>
              <li>Forgetting to use the toilet before bed?</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Relieving Factors (or attempted interventions):</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Fluid restriction in the evening?</li>
              <li>Scheduled waking at night to void? (By whom? Successful?)</li>
              <li>Use of bedwetting alarms? (Ever tried? Success rate?)</li>
              <li>Medications? (e.g., Desmopressin (DDAVP), Imipramine - past or
                current use, effectiveness, side effects)</li>
              <li>Positive reinforcement / reward charts?</li>
              <li>Addressing constipation?</li>
              <li>Avoiding known dietary triggers?</li>
              <li>Child spontaneously wakes to void on some nights?</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>C: Character (of the wetting episode)</strong>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Volume of urine:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Small amount, just damp?</li>
              <li>Large amount, soaking through bedding?</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Timing of wetting:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Typically occurs </li>
              <ul>
                <li>early in the night, </li>
                <li>middle, or </li>
                <li>towards morning?</li>
              </ul>
              <li>Does the child wake up after wetting, or sleep through it?</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Nature of stream (if observed during daytime voiding):</strong>
            Strong, weak, interrupted? (Relevant if daytime symptoms are also
            present).</li>
          <li>Is the child aware of the sensation of needing to urinate before
            wetting at night?</li>
          <li>Any straining or difficulty initiating urination (day or night)?</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>R: Radiation</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Not applicable to bedwetting itself.</li>
          <li><em>This element is not typically used for enuresis.</em></li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>A: Associated Symptoms</strong>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Daytime Urinary Symptoms (Crucial to ask, as it may
              indicate underlying bladder dysfunction rather than simple
              nocturnal enuresis):</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Daytime incontinence (wetting)?</li>
              <li>Urgency (sudden, strong need to urinate)?</li>
              <li>Frequency (urinating more often than usual)?</li>
              <li>Hesitancy (difficulty starting urine stream)?</li>
              <li>Straining to urinate?</li>
              <li>Intermittent stream?</li>
              <li>Dribbling or post-void dribbling?</li>
              <li>Pain or burning during urination (dysuria) (suggests UTI)?</li>
              <li>Holding maneuvers (e.g., squatting, leg crossing, pressing on
                perineum to prevent wetting)?</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Bowel Symptoms:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Constipation (frequency of bowel movements, stool consistency,
                straining, pain)? (Very common co-morbidity)</li>
              <li>Encopresis (fecal soiling)?</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Sleep-Related Symptoms:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Snoring, observed apneas, restless sleep (suggests
                sleep-disordered breathing, which can contribute)?</li>
              <li>Difficulty waking the child?</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Neurological Symptoms:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Weakness or changes in gait?</li>
              <li>Back pain, sacral dimple, hairy patch over the spine (suggests
                possible spinal cord abnormality like spina bifida occulta)?</li>
              <li>Changes in bowel/bladder control that are new and sudden
                (beyond just wetting).</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>General/Systemic:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Increased thirst (polydipsia) and increased urination
                (polyuria) (suggests diabetes mellitus or diabetes insipidus)?</li>
              <li>Fever, malaise (suggests infection)?</li>
              <li>Poor growth, failure to thrive?</li>
              <li>Edema (swelling)?</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Psychological/Behavioral:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Recent stressors or changes in family/school environment?</li>
              <li>Signs of anxiety, depression, or behavioral problems?</li>
              <li>Child's emotional reaction to bedwetting (embarrassment,
                guilt, shame)?</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>P: Pattern (Frequency)</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>How many nights per week does bedwetting occur? (e.g., every
            night, 3-4 times/week, occasionally)</li>
          <li>How many times per night does wetting occur? (Once, multiple
            times)</li>
          <li>Is there any pattern to dry nights vs. wet nights?</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>P: Progression</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Is the frequency/severity of bedwetting increasing, decreasing, or
            staying the same over time?</li>
          <li>Any changes in associated symptoms?</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li> <strong>E: Effect on life (Child and Family)</strong>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Child:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Emotional impact (shame, embarrassment, guilt, low
                self-esteem, anxiety)?</li>
              <li>Impact on social activities (e.g., avoiding sleepovers,
                camps)?</li>
              <li>Impact on sleep quality?</li>
              <li>Child's perception of the problem? (Are they bothered by it?)</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><strong>Family:</strong>
            <ul>
              <li>Parental stress, frustration, or anxiety?</li>
              <li>Impact on family routines (e.g., laundry burden)?</li>
              <li>Impact on siblings?</li>
              <li>Any punitive measures used (which are generally discouraged)?</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><em>R</em>:<em>Red flags</em></li>
      <ul>
        <li><br>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <li><strong>S: Severity / Scale</strong>
        <ul>
          <li>Often judged by:
            <ul>
              <li>Frequency of wet nights per week.</li>
              <li>Number of wetting episodes per night.</li>
              <li>Volume of urine (small vs. soaking).</li>
              <li>Impact on the child's and family's quality of life.</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li><em>A specific numerical scale for bedwetting itself is not
              standard, but these factors contribute to assessing clinical
              significance.</em></li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <h3>Additional Contextual Information to Gather for Bedwetting:</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Developmental History:</strong> Milestones achieved, any
        developmental delays.</li>
      <li><strong>Family History:</strong> History of enuresis in parents or
        siblings (strong genetic component).</li>
      <li><strong>Fluid Intake:</strong> Type and amount of fluids consumed
        throughout the day, especially in the evening.</li>
      <li><strong>Toileting Habits/Training:</strong> Age of toilet training,
        current daytime toileting routine, resistance to using toilet.</li>
      <li><strong>Sleep Patterns:</strong> Bedtime, typical sleep duration,
        depth of sleep, any sleep disturbances.</li>
      <li><strong>Psychosocial Environment:</strong> Major life changes, family
        stressors, school environment, peer relationships.</li>
      <li><strong>Past Medical History:</strong> Previous UTIs, kidney problems,
        neurological conditions, diabetes, sickle cell disease.</li>
    </ul>





<h2>Elaboration of Presenting Complaint: Night Terrors (Pavor Nocturnus)</h2>

<ul>
    <li>
        <strong>S: Site (of Manifestation)</strong>
        <ul>
            <li>Where does the event primarily occur? (e.g., child's bed, another room if sleepwalking is involved).</li>
            <li>Are there any physical signs observed on the child during or after the episode (e.g., sweating, flushed face)?</li>
            <li><em>"Site" is less about a location of pain and more about the setting and physical manifestations.</em></li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>O: Onset</strong>
        <ul>
            <li>At what age did the night terrors first begin?</li>
            <li>Was there any specific trigger or event around the time they started (e.g., illness, stress, change in routine, new medication)?</li>
            <li>Did they start suddenly or was there a gradual increase in frequency/intensity?</li>
            <li class="pediatric">Night terrors typically begin in early childhood, often between ages 3-7, but can occur earlier or later.</li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>D: Duration</strong>
        <ul>
            <li>How long does a typical night terror episode last? (Usually a few minutes, but can range from 1 to 10+ minutes).</li>
            <li>How long has the child been experiencing these episodes overall (weeks, months, years)?</li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>A: Aggravating / Relieving Factors</strong>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Aggravating Factors (Triggers):</strong>
                <ul>
                    <li>Sleep deprivation or irregular sleep schedules?</li>
                    <li>Fever or illness?</li>
                    <li>Stress, anxiety, or exciting/upsetting events during the day?</li>
                    <li>Full bladder?</li>
                    <li>Noisy sleep environment or other disturbances during sleep?</li>
                    <li>Certain medications (e.g., some stimulants, sedatives, antihistamines)?</li>
                    <li>Traveling or sleeping in an unfamiliar environment?</li>
                    <li class="pediatric">Growth spurts or developmental changes?</li>
                    <li class="pediatric">Family history of parasomnias (night terrors, sleepwalking)?</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Relieving Factors (or attempted interventions during/after an episode):</strong>
                <ul>
                    <li>Does waking the child fully stop the episode? (Usually difficult to wake, and may lead to confusion if woken).</li>
                    <li>What do caregivers typically do during an episode? (e.g., try to comfort, hold, speak to the child – often with little effect during the terror itself).</li>
                    <li>Does ensuring adequate sleep and a regular sleep schedule help reduce frequency?</li>
                    <li>Scheduled awakenings (waking the child briefly about 15-30 minutes before episodes typically occur, if predictable)?</li>
                    <li>Creating a safe sleep environment to prevent injury?</li>
                    <li>Reassurance after the child fully awakens (though they usually have no memory of the event)?</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>C: Character (Description of the Episode)</strong>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Child's Appearance and Behavior During Episode:</strong>
                <ul>
                    <li>Sudden arousal from sleep?</li>
                    <li>Intense crying, screaming, shouting?</li>
                    <li>Signs of intense fear or panic (e.g., wide eyes, terrified expression)?</li>
                    <li>Sitting up in bed, thrashing, kicking, flailing?</li>
                    <li>May appear confused, disoriented, and unresponsive to comfort or attempts to awaken.</li>
                    <li>Eyes may be open with a "glassy" stare.</li>
                    <li>Sweating, rapid breathing (tachypnea), rapid heart rate (tachycardia), flushed skin, dilated pupils?</li>
                    <li>May mumble, speak incoherently, or not speak at all.</li>
                    <li>Sleepwalking (somnambulism) may co-occur.</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Child's State After the Episode:</strong>
                <ul>
                    <li>Usually returns to sleep quickly without fully waking up.</li>
                    <li>Amnesia for the event: Child has no memory of the terror, dream, or behaviors the next morning.</li>
                    <li>If awakened during an episode, the child may be confused, disoriented, and agitated for a period.</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li>Is there any dream content recalled by the child? (Typically no, unlike nightmares).</li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>R: Radiation</strong>
        <ul>
            <li>Not applicable to night terrors.</li>
            <li><em>This element is not used for describing parasomnias.</em></li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>A: Associated Symptoms (Daytime or other sleep-related)</strong>
        <ul>
            <li>Daytime sleepiness or fatigue (if episodes are frequent or disruptive to overall sleep)?</li>
            <li>Behavioral problems or mood changes during the day?</li>
            <li>Other sleep problems:
                <ul>
                    <li>Sleepwalking (somnambulism)?</li>
                    <li>Sleep talking (somniloquy)?</li>
                    <li>Nightmares (distinct from night terrors – child usually remembers the dream and is easily comforted)?</li>
                    <li>Bruxism (teeth grinding)?</li>
                    <li>Restless Leg Syndrome symptoms?</li>
                    <li>Snoring or signs of sleep-disordered breathing (e.g., gasping, pauses in breathing observed by caregiver)?</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li>Symptoms of anxiety or stress?</li>
            <li class="pediatric">Headaches, especially if there's concern about underlying neurological issues or sleep deprivation.</li>
            <li class="pediatric">Enuresis (bedwetting) can sometimes co-occur with other parasomnias.</li>
            <li class="pediatric">Signs of underlying medical conditions that could trigger night terrors (e.g., GERD causing discomfort, fever).</li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>P: Pattern (Timing / Frequency of Episodes)</strong>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Timing during the night:</strong>
                <ul>
                    <li>Typically occur in the first third of the night (during deep non-REM sleep, stages N3). Usually 1-3 hours after falling asleep.</li>
                    <li>Rarely occur during naps.</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Frequency:</strong>
                <ul>
                    <li>How many episodes per night/week/month?</li>
                    <li>Are they clustered (several nights in a row then a period without)?</li>
                    <li>Is the frequency increasing, decreasing, or stable?</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li>Is there a predictable time each night when they occur?</li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>P: Progression</strong>
        <ul>
            <li>How have the night terrors changed since they first started? (e.g., become more intense, more frequent, less frequent, associated with new behaviors like sleepwalking).</li>
            <li class="pediatric">Night terrors often decrease in frequency and resolve spontaneously as the child gets older, usually by adolescence.</li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>E: Effect on life (Child and Family)</strong>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Child:</strong>
                <ul>
                    <li>Although the child doesn't remember the episode, is there any observed daytime sleepiness, fatigue, or mood changes?</li>
                    <li>Risk of injury during an episode (e.g., falling out of bed, hitting objects if sleepwalking)?</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li><strong>Family:</strong>
                <ul>
                    <li>Significant distress, anxiety, and sleep disruption for parents/caregivers witnessing the episodes.</li>
                    <li>Concern about the child's well-being or potential underlying problems.</li>
                    <li>Impact on family sleep quality.</li>
                    <li>Strain on parental relationships due to stress and sleep loss.</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
        </ul>
    </li>
    <li>
        <strong>S: Severity / Scale</strong>
        <ul>
            <li>Severity is often judged by:
                <ul>
                    <li>Frequency and intensity of episodes.</li>
                    <li>Degree of disruption to the child's and family's sleep.</li>
                    <li>Risk of injury.</li>
                    <li>Level of distress experienced by caregivers.</li>
                </ul>
            </li>
            <li><em>A specific numerical scale for night terror severity is not standard, but these factors assess clinical significance.</em></li>
        </ul>
    </li>
</ul>

<h3>Additional Contextual Information to Gather for Night Terrors:</h3>
<ul>
    <li>Detailed sleep history: Bedtime, wake time, total sleep duration, sleep hygiene practices, nap schedule.</li>
    <li>Family history of parasomnias (night terrors, sleepwalking, nightmares), sleep disorders, or psychiatric conditions.</li>
    <li>Child's daily routine, school performance, social interactions.</li>
    <li>Any recent significant life events or stressors.</li>
    <li>Medication history (prescription, over-the-counter, supplements).</li>
    <li>Caffeine or stimulant intake (especially in older children/adolescents).</li>
    <li>Screen time habits, especially before bed.</li>
    <li>Previous evaluations or treatments for the night terrors or other sleep problems.</li>
</ul>

    <p>Negative History: </p>
    <ol>
      <li>Mention relevant negative findings related to the presenting illness,
        e.g., No h/o fever, vomiting, loose stools, seizures, etc.</li>
    </ol>
    <p></p>
